{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e2b2aac-574a-484a-a5dc-89c4bf165941","content":"The process isn't running on this machine, but here's exactly how to diagnose and configure:\n\n## 1. Determine the Runtime\n\nRun these on **your** machine:\n\n```bash\n# Check for CoreCLR — if this returns output, it's CoreCLR\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -i 'libcoreclr\\|libclrjit'\n\n# Check for NativeAOT — no coreclr/clrjit means NativeAOT\n# NativeAOT apps are single-file with no managed runtime libraries\n```\n\nIf `libcoreclr.so` appears in the maps → **CoreCLR**. If not → **NativeAOT**.\n\nYou can also check:\n```bash\n# NativeAOT binaries are statically linked, so:\nreadelf -d /proc/12345/exe | grep -i NEEDED\n# CoreCLR will show libcoreclr.so dependency; NativeAOT won't\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### For CoreCLR:\n```bash\n# Set environment variables (before launching the app):\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full heap dump (Triage=1, Mini=2, Heap=3, Full=4)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n\n# Create the dump directory:\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n\n# Also set the OS-level core pattern:\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%p' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\n### For NativeAOT:\nNativeAOT doesn't support the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump*` variables. Use **OS-level** core dumps only:\n\n```bash\n# Configure Linux kernel core dumps:\necho '/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n\n# Optionally use systemd-coredump (if using systemd):\nsudo apt install systemd-coredump   # Debian/Ubuntu\ncoredumpctl list                     # view collected dumps\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Make It Persistent\n\nTo survive reboots, add to `/etc/sysctl.conf`:\n```\nkernel.core_pattern=/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t\n```\nAnd add `ulimit -c unlimited` to your app's service file or launch script.\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** Check `/proc/<PID>/maps` for `libcoreclr` — if found, use `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump`; if not (NativeAOT), rely on Linux `core_pattern`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a4c1626c-3033-4ccb-913c-cb54f8bfe7a2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected — I'm not on the user's machine. Let me give them guidance on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps accordingly.","outputTokens":760,"requestId":"DA0B:3CD6DC:57D343:64646C:6A03DA06"},"id":"6c351cf1-52be-4ef2-926e-8e2c26b8bb23","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:55:37.783Z","parentId":"15d3d57c-c118-4091-8c5f-c39aecc073f8"}
